NSA surveillance
Broader|Mass surveillanceThe practice of mass surveillance in the United States dates back to World War I Censorship in the United States#Wartime censorship|wartime monitoring and censorship of international communications from, to, or which passed through the United States. After the First World War and the Second World War, the surveillance continued, via programs such as the Black Chamber and Project SHAMROCK. The formation and growth of federal Law enforcement agency|law-enforcement and Intelligence agency|intelligence agencies such as the FBI, CIA, and NSA institutionalized surveillance used to also silence political dissent, as evidenced by COINTELPRO projects which targeted various organizations and individuals. During the Civil Rights Movement era, many individuals put under surveillance orders were first labelled as integrationists then deemed subversive. Other targeted individuals and groups included Native American activists, African American and Chicano liberation movement activists, and anti-war protesters.

The formation of the international UKUSA surveillance agreement of 1946 evolved into the ECHELON collaboration by 1955<ref>cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/02/history-of-5-eyes-explainer|title=History of 5-Eyes – explainer|first=Paul|last=Farrell|date=2 December 2013|accessdate=14 October 2017|website=Theguardian.com</ref> of five English-speaking nations, also known as the Five Eyes, and focused on interception of electronic communications, with substantial increases in domestic surveillance capabilities.<ref>cite web|url=https://giswatch.org/en/communications-surveillance/unmasking-five-eyes-global-surveillance-practices|title=Unmasking the Five Eyes' global surveillance practices - GISWatch|website=giswatch.org|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref>

Following the September 11th attacks of 2001, domestic and international mass surveillance capabilities escalated intensely. Contemporary mass surveillance relies upon annual presidential executive orders declaring a continued State of National Emergency, first signed by George W. Bush on September 14, 2001 and then continued on an annual basis by President Barack Obama,<ref>cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/all/obama-quietly-extends-post-911-state|title=Obama quietly extends post-9/11 state of national emergency|website=Msnbc.com|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref> and upon several subsequent national security Acts including the USA PATRIOT Act and FISA Amendment Act's PRISM (surveillance program)|PRISM surveillance program. Critics and political dissenters currently describe the effects of these acts, orders, and resulting database network of Fusion centers as forming a veritable American police state that simply institutionalized the illegal COINTELPRO tactics used to assassinate dissenters and leaders from the 1950s onwards.<ref>cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/lists/the-new-political-prisoners-leakers-hackers-and-activists-20130301|title=The New Political Prisoners: Leakers, Hackers and Activists|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref><ref>cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/us/20160706/1042493824/political-prisoners-suffer-in-america.html|title=US Political Prisoners: What Washington Doesn't Want You to Know|website=Sputniknews.com|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref><ref>cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2014/2/25/exclusive_inside_the_army_spy_ring|title=Exclusive: Inside the Army Spy Ring & Attempted Entrapment of Peace Activists, Iraq Vets, Anarchists|website=Democracynow.org|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref><ref>cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2012/12/27/the_fbi_vs_occupy_secret_docs|title=The FBI vs. Occupy: Secret Docs Reveal "Counterterrorism" Monitoring of OWS from Its Earliest Days|website=Democracynow.org|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref>

Additional surveillance agencies, such as the DHS and the position of Director of National Intelligence have exponentially escalated mass surveillance since 2001. A series of 2013 mass surveillance disclosures|media reports in 2013 revealed more recent programs and techniques employed by the United States Intelligence Community|US intelligence community.<ref>cite web
|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/31/nsa-top-secret-program-online-data
|title = XKeyscore: NSA tool collects 'nearly everything a user does on the internet'
