</ref>
Advances in computer and information technology allow the creation of huge National databases of United States persons|national databases that facilitate mass surveillance in the United States<ref>name=guardian6</ref> by DHS managed Fusion centers, the CIA's Terrorist Threat Integration Center (TTIC) program, and the FBI's Terrorist Screening Database|TSDB.

Mass surveillance databases are also cited as responsible for profiling Latino Americans and contributing to "self-deportation" techniques, or physical deportations by way of the DHS's ICEGang national database.<ref>cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/08/11/u-s-government-using-gang-databases-to-deport-undocumented-immigrants/|title=Marked for Life: U.S. Government Using Gang Databases to Deport Undocumented Immigrants|first=Ali|last=Winston|date=11 August 2016|website=Theintercept.com|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref>

History and Overview
Mass surveillance in the United States can be traced back to the early 20th century, when all international mail sent through the U.S. Postal Service and international cables sent through companies such as Western Union, ITT Corporation|ITT, and RCA were sent under the surveillance authority of the Bureau of Investigation, later renamed the Federal Bureau of Investigation,<ref>Curt Gentry, "J.Edgar Hoover: The Man and the Secrets", NY; Norton and Co., 2001.</ref> and reviewed by the US military.<ref>James Bamford, The Shadow Factory, 2008, Doubleday, Chapter 'Shamrock', especially pg. 163</ref>

After World War I, the US Army and State Department established the Black Chamber, also known as the Cipher Bureau, which began operations in 1919.<ref>Cite web|url=https://www.nsa.gov/about/cryptologic-heritage/center-cryptologic-history/pre-1952-timeline/|title=Pre-1952 Historical Timeline|website=www.nsa.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-11-06</ref> The Black Chamber was headed by Herbert Yardley|Herbert O. Yardley, who had been a leader in the Army's Military Intelligence program. Regarded as a precursor to the National Security Agency, it conducted peacetime decryption of material including diplomatic communications until 1929.<ref name="reutershistory">cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/07/us-usa-security-records-factbox-idUSBRE95617O20130607|title=Factbox: History of mass surveillance in the United States|date=7 June 2013|accessdate=14 August 2013|agency=Reuters</ref><ref>cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/about/cryptologic_heritage/hall_of_honor/1999/yardley.shtml|title=Hall of Honor 1999 Inductee – Herbert O. Yardley|publisher=NSA</ref>

In the advent of World War II, the Office of Censorship was established. The wartime agency monitored "communications by mail, cable, radio, or other means of transmission passing between the United States and any foreign country".<ref name="Fiset2001">[https://www.archives.gov/publications/prologue/2001/spring/mail-censorship-in-world-war-two-1.html "Return to Sender: U.S. Censorship of Enemy Alien Mail in World War II"], Louis Fiset, ''Prologue Magazine'', Vol. 33, No. 1 (Spring 2001). Retrieved 5 October 2013.</ref> This included the 350,000 overseas cables and telegrams and 25,000 international telephone calls made each week of.<ref name="kennett1985">cite book | title=For the duration... : the United States goes to war, Pearl Harbor-1942 | publisher=Scribner | author=Kennett, Lee | year=1985 | location=New York | isbn=0-684-18239-4</ref>rp|144 "Every letter that crossed international or U.S. territorial borders from December 1941 to August 1945 was subject to being opened and scoured for details."<ref name="Fiset2001" />

With the end of World War II, Project SHAMROCK was established in 1945.  The organization was created to accumulate telegraphic data entering and exiting from the United States.<ref name="reutershistory" /><ref>cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/publications/publi00015.cfm|title=The Origins of NSA (NSA.gov)|last=The Center for Cryptologic History|publisher=Web.archive.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040318034627/http://www.nsa.gov/publications/publi00015.cfm|archivedate=18 March 2004</ref> Major communication companies such as Western Union, RCA|RCA Global and ITT Corporation|ITT World Communications actively aided the project, allowing American intelligence officials to gain access to international message traffic.<ref name="pbs">cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/homefront/preemption/churchfisa.html|title=The Church Committee Hearings & the FISA Court|last1=Epsley-Jones|first1=Katelyn|last2=Frenzel|first2=Christina|publisher=PBS|accessdate=14 August 2013</ref> Under the project, and many subsequent programs, no precedent had been established for judicial authorisation, and no warrants were issued for surveillance activities. The project was terminated in 1975.<ref name="reutershistory" />

In 1952, President Harry S. Truman established the National Security Agency (National Security Agency (NSA)|NSA) in 1952 for the purposes of collecting, processing, and monitoring intelligence data.<ref>Cite web|url=https://www.nsa.gov/news-features/declassified-documents/truman/assets/files/truman-memo.pdf|title=Memorandum|last=Truman|first=Harry S.|date=October 24, 1952|website=National Security Agency|access-date=</ref> The existence of NSA was not known to people as the memorandum by President Truman was classified.<ref>Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/no-such-agency-spies-on-the-communications-of-the-world/2013/06/06/5bcd46a6-ceb9-11e2-8845-d970ccb04497_story.html|title='No Such Agency' spies on the communications of the world|last=Gearan|first=Anne|date=2013-06-06|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-11-06|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286</ref>

When the Citizens' Commission to Investigate the FBI published stolen FBI documents revealing abuse of intelligence programs in 1971, Senator Frank Church began an investigation into the programs that become known as the Church Committee. The committee sought to investigate intelligence abuses throughout the 1970s.  Following a report provided by the committee outlining egregious abuse, in 1976 Congress established the United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence|Senate Select Committee on Intelligence. It would later be joined by the United States Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court|Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court in 1978.<ref name="reutershistory" /> The institutions worked to limit the power of the agencies, ensuring that surveillance activities remained within the rule of law.<ref>Cite web|url=http://prospect.org/print/V12/19/mooney-c.html|title=TAP: Vol 12, Iss. 19. Back to Church. Chris Mooney.|date=2006-12-05|access-date=2017-11-06|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205025524/http://prospect.org/print/V12/19/mooney-c.html|archivedate=2006-12-05|df=</ref>

Following the attacks of September 11, 2001, United States Congress|Congress passed The Patriot Act to strengthen security and intelligence efforts., The act granted the President broad powers on the War against Terror|war against terror, including the power to bypass the FISA Court for surveillance orders in cases of national security. Additionally, mass surveillance activities were conducted alongside various other surveillance programs under the head of President's Surveillance Program.<ref>Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/interactive/2013/jun/27/nsa-inspector-general-report-document-data-collection|title=NSA inspector general report on email and internet data collection under Stellar Wind – full document|date=2013-06-27|website=the Guardian|access-date=2017-11-06</ref> Under pressure from the public, the warrantless wiretapping program was allegedly ended in January 2007.<ref>Cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/politics/20060117gonzales_Letter.pdf|title=The New York Times|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=</ref>

Many details about the surveillance activities conducted in the United States were revealed in the disclosure by Edward Snowden in June 2013.<ref>Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2013/jun/09/nsa-whistleblower-edward-snowden-interview-video|title=NSA whistleblower Edward Snowden: 'I don't want to live in a society that does these sort of things' – video|last=Poitras|first=Laura|date=2013-06-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-11-20|last2=Greenwald|first2=Glenn|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077</ref><ref name="guardian-2013">Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/us-intelligence-mining-data-from-nine-us-internet-companies-in-broad-secret-program/2013/06/06/3a0c0da8-cebf-11e2-8845-d970ccb04497_story.html|title=U.S., British intelligence mining data from nine U.S. Internet companies in broad secret program|last=Gellman|first=Barton|date=2013-06-07|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-11-06|last2=Poitras|first2=Laura|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286</ref> Regarded as one of the biggest media leaks in the United States, it presented extensive details about the surveillance programs of the NSA, that involved interception of internet data and telephonic calls from over a billion users, across various countries.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="guardian-2013" />

National Security Agency (NSA)
File:Vietnam War protest in Washington DC April 1971.jpg|thumb|At the request of the U.S. Army, those who protested against the Vietnam War were put on the NSA's "watch list".<ref name="pbs"/>
1947: The National Security Act was signed by President Truman, establishing a National Security Council.<ref>cite web |url=http://www.democraticunderground.com/10022984639 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-08-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817032009/http://www.democraticunderground.com/10022984639 |archivedate=2016-08-17 |df= </ref>

1949: The Armed Forces Security Agency was established to coordinate signal operations between military branches.<ref>cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2010/11/the-national-security-agency-is-established-nov-4-1952-044671|title=The National Security Agency is established, Nov. 4, 1952|website=Politico.com|accessdate=14 October 2017</ref>

1952: The National Security Agency (NSA) was officially established by President Truman by way of a National Security Council Intelligence Directive 9, dated Oct. 24, while the NSA officially came into existence days later on Nov. 4.<ref name="reutershistory"/> According to ''The New York Times'', the NSA was created in "absolute secrecy" by President Truman,<ref>cite news |last=Bamford |first=James |title=The Agency That Could Be Big Brother|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/25/weekinreview/25bamford.html?pagewanted=print|work=The New York Times|accessdate=14 August 2013 |date=25 December 2005</ref>  whose surveillance-minded administration ordered, only six weeks after President Truman took office, Telephone tapping|wiretaps on the telephones of Thomas Gardiner Corcoran, a close advisor of Franklin D. Roosevelt.<ref>cite news|last=DAVID BURNHAM|title=TRUMAN WIRETAPS ON EX-NEW DEAL AIDE CITED|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/02/01/us/truman-wiretaps-on-ex-new-deal-aide-cited.html|publisher=''The New York Times''|accessdate=18 September 2013|date=1 February 1986</ref> The recorded conversations are currently kept at the Harry S. Truman Presidential Library and Museum, along with other documents considered sensitive ([http://www.trumanlibrary.org/hstpaper/psf.htm ≈233,600 pages]).

Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
Institutional domestic surveillance was founded in 1896 with the National Bureau of Criminal Identification, which evolved by 1908 into the Bureau of Investigation, operated under the authority of the Department of Justice. In 1935, the FBI had grown into an independent agency under the direction of J. Edgar Hoover whose staff, through the use of wire taps, cable taps, mail tampering, garbage filtering and infiltrators, prepared secret FBI Index Lists on more than 10 million people by 1939.<ref>Curt Gentry, "J.Edgar Hoover: The Man and the Secrets". NY; Norton and Co., 2001.</ref>

Purported to be chasing 'communists' and other alleged subversives, the FBI used public and private pressure to destroy the lives of those it targeted during McCarthyism, including those lives of the Hollywood 10 with the Hollywood blacklist. The FBI's surveillance and investigation roles expanded in the 1950s while using the collected information to facilitate political assassinations, including the murders of Fred Hampton and Mark Clark in 1969. The FBI is also directly connected to the bombings, assassinations, and deaths of other people including Malcolm X in 1963, Viola Liuzzo in 1965, Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. in 1968, Anna Mae Pictou Aquash in 1976, and Judi Bari in 1990.citation needed|date=May 2018

As the extent of the FBI's domestic surveillance continued to grow, many celebrities were also secretly investigated by the bureau, including:
* First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt – A vocal critic of Hoover who likened the FBI to an 'American Gestapo' for its Index lists.<ref>Curt Gentry, "J. Edgar Hoover: The Man and the Secrets", NY; Norton and Co, 2001</ref> Roosevelt also spoke out against anti-Japanese prejudice during the second world war, and was later a delegate to the United Nations and instrumental in creating the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. The [http://vault.fbi.gov/Eleanor%20Roosevelt 3,000-page] FBI dossier on Eleanor Roosevelt reveals Hoover's close monitoring of her activities and writings, and contains retaliatory charges against her for suspected Communist activities.<ref>cite web|title=Question: Why is Eleanor Roosevelt's FBI file so large?|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~erpapers/teachinger/q-and-a/q31.cfm|publisher=George Washington University|accessdate=18 September 2013</ref><ref>cite web|title=Eleanor Roosevelt|url=http://www.history.com/topics/eleanor-roosevelt|publisher=History (U.S. TV channel)|accessdate=18 September 2013|quote=J. Edgar Hoover (1895–1972), the longtime director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation, considered Eleanor Roosevelt's liberal views dangerous and believed she might be involved in communist activities. He ordered his agents to monitor Roosevelt and keep what became an extensive file on her.</ref>
* Frank Sinatra – His [http://vault.fbi.gov/Frank%20Sinatra 1,300 page] FBI dossier, dating from 1943, contains allegations about Sinatra's possible ties to the American Communist Party. The FBI spent several decades tracking Sinatra and his associates.<ref>cite news|author1=RONALD J. OSTROW  |author2=LISA GETTER |lastauthoramp=yes |title=FBI Files on Sinatra Detail Links to JFK, Mob Figures|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/dec/09/news/mn-52274|publisher=''Los Angeles Times''|accessdate=18 September 2013|date=9 December 1998</ref><ref>cite news|last=MOLOTSKY|first=IRVIN|title=F.B.I. Releases Its Sinatra File, With Tidbits Old and New|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/09/us/fbi-releases-its-sinatra-file-with-tidbits-old-and-new.html|publisher=''The New York Times''|accessdate=18 September 2013|date=9 December 1998</ref>
* Marilyn Monroe – Her FBI dossier begins in 1955 and continues up until the months before her death. It focuses mostly on her travels and associations, searching for signs of leftist views and possible ties to communism.<ref name="apmonroe">cite web|title=FBI removes many redactions in Marilyn Monroe file|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/fbi-removes-many-redactions-marilyn-monroe-file|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=18 September 2013</ref> Her ex-husband, Arthur Miller, was also monitored. Monroe's FBI dossier is "heavily censored", but a [http://vault.fbi.gov/Marilyn%20Monroe "reprocessed" version] has been released by the FBI to the public.<ref name="apmonroe"/>
* John Lennon –  In 1971, shortly after Lennon arrived in the United States on a visa to meet up with Anti-war movement|anti-war activists, the FBI placed Lennon under surveillance, and the U.S. government tried to deport him from the country.<ref name="nytimesbeatles">cite news|last=Cohen|first=Adam|title=While Nixon Campaigned, the F.B.I. Watched John Lennon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/21/opinion/21thu4.html|publisher=''The New York Times''|accessdate=18 September 2013|date=21 September 2006</ref> At that time, opposition to the Vietnam War had reached a peak and Lennon often showed up at political rallies to sing his anti-war anthem "''Give Peace a Chance''".<ref name="nytimesbeatles"/> The U.S. government argued that Lennon's [http://vault.fbi.gov/john-winston-lennon 300 page] FBI dossier was particularly sensitive because its release may "lead to foreign diplomatic, economic and military retaliation against the United States",<ref>cite news|last=Gumbel |first=Andrew |title=The Lennon Files: The FBI and the Beatle |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/the-lennon-files-the-fbi-and-the-beatle-5938422.html |publisher=''The Independent'' |accessdate=18 September 2013 |location=London |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004031344/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/the-lennon-files-the-fbi-and-the-beatle-5938422.html |archivedate=October 4, 2015 
</ref> and therefore only approved a "heavily censored" version.<ref>cite web|last=Laurent Belsie|title=US hoped to deport John Lennon|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1983/0323/032325.html|publisher=''The Christian Science Monitor''|accessdate=18 September 2013</ref>
* The Beatles, of which John Lennon was a member, had a [http://vault.fbi.gov/The%20Beatles separate FBI dossier].

