Some of the greatest historical figures of the 20th century, including several U.S. citizens, were placed under warrantless surveillance for the purpose of character assassination – a process that aims to destroy the credibility and reputation of a person, institution, or nation.

clear
Left: Albert Einstein, who supported the anti-war movement and opposed nuclear proliferation, was a member of numerous civil rights groups including the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (See Albert Einstein's political views). As a result of his political views, Einstein was subjected to telephone tapping, and his mail was searched by the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) as part of a secret government campaign that aimed to link him with a Soviet espionage ring in order to first discredit him, and then deport him (unsuccessfully) from the United States.<ref>cite news|title=New Details Emerge From the Einstein Files; How the F.B.I. Tracked His Phone Calls and His Trash|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/07/science/new-details-emerge-einstein-files-fbi-tracked-his-phone-calls-his-trash.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|publisher=''The New York Times''|accessdate=17 September 2013|first=Dennis|last=Overbye|date=7 May 2002</ref><ref>cite news|title=FBI campaign against Einstein revealed|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sci/tech/2033324.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=17 September 2013|date=8 June 2002</ref><ref>cite web|title=Albert Einstein: Fact or Fiction?|url=http://www.history.com/topics/einsteins-life-facts-and-fiction|publisher=History (U.S. TV channel)|accessdate=17 September 2013|quote=Because of his controversial political beliefs-his support for socialism, civil rights, and nuclear disarmament, for example-many anti-Communist crusaders believed that Einstein was a dangerous subversive. Some, like FBI director J. Edgar Hoover, even thought he was a spy. For 22 years, Hoover's agents tapped Einstein's phones, opened his mail, rifled through his trash and even bugged his secretary's nephew's house, all to prove that he was more radical (as his 1,500-page FBI dossier noted) than "even Stalin himself."</ref>

Center: Martin Luther King, Jr., a leader of the Civil Rights Movement, was the target of an intensive campaign by the FBI to "neutralize" him as an effective civil rights activist.<ref name=Church>citation|last=Church|first= Frank|authorlink= Frank Church|title= Church Committee Book III| work =Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., Case Study| publisher= Church Committee| date=April 23, 1976</ref> A FBI memo recognized King to be the "most dangerous and effective Negro leader in the country.",<ref name="mlkcommunism">cite news|title=FBI tracked King's every move|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/US/03/31/mlk.fbi.conspiracy/|publisher=CNN|accessdate=17 September 2013|date=29 December 2008</ref>  and the agency wanted to discredit him by collecting evidence to (unsuccessfully) prove that he had been influenced by communism.<ref name="mlkcommunism"/>

Right: Daniel Ellsberg, who leaked the Pentagon Papers to the media in 1971, experienced one of the most spectacular episodes of government surveillance and character assassination. The White House tried to steal his medical records and other possibly detrimental information by sending a special unit to break into the office of Ellsberg's psychiatrist.<ref>cite web|title='Life Lessons' From a White House Plumber|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=14468307|publisher=NPR|quote=When Daniel Ellsberg leaked the Pentagon Papers to The New York Times in 1971, the Nixon White House tried to discredit him. Among other things, Nixon loyalists burglarized the office of Ellsberg's psychiatrist.</ref><ref>cite news|title=The Watergate Story|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/watergate/timeline.html|publisher=''The Washington Post''|accessdate=17 September 2013|quote=The White House "plumbers" unit – named for their orders to plug leaks in the administration – burglarizes a psychiatrist's office to find files on Daniel Ellsberg, the former defense analyst who leaked the Pentagon Papers.</ref> These activities were later uncovered during the course of investigation as the Watergate scandal slowly unfolded, which eventually led to the resignation of President Richard Nixon.<ref>cite web|title=Watergate and the Constitution|url=https://www.archives.gov/education/lessons/watergate-constitution/|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration|accessdate=17 September 2013</ref>

See also: The FBI kept a dossier criminal|dossier on Albert Einstein ([http://vault.fbi.gov/Albert%20Einstein ≈1,500 pages]) and Martin Luther King, Jr. ([http://vault.fbi.gov/Martin%20Luther%20King,%20Jr. ≈17,000 pages]). Due to a court order, however, some information has been removed and many other pages will not be released until the year 2027.<ref>cite web|title=Martin Luther King, Jr. FBI File|url=http://library.truman.edu/microforms/martin_luther_king.asp|publisher=Pickler Memorial Library (Truman State University)|accessdate=17 September 2013</ref>
